<br>
Correct me if I'm wrong, but couldn't a *controlled* source of neutrons be valuable? I probably don't know enough about it, but I thought the reaction rate of a reactor was controlled via moderators/neutron absorbers. Using a moderator (e.g. Graphite rod) means that the reaction has the possibility of going prompt-critical on its own. Now if we had a controllable source of neutrons, we could fizzle at much higher rates without fear of a runaway reaction. If the sonics stop, so does the reaction.<br>
<br>
Thinking in line with the theme of this site, doesn't that mean that a NTR engine could be more easily controlled? Micro-controllers could monitor the temperature of the engine. As the cooling effect from the propellant reduces the amount of heat in the engine, the fission rate can be adjusted to generate more power. Similarly, as the flow rate lessens, the fission rate can be lessened. This would be particularly useful for an &quot;open air&quot; system like a space plane. The amount of cooling at any given time could be difficult to compensate for. A neutron source with a high reaction time could be the key to making the engines run at peak efficiency.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=astronuc>Astronuc</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 99<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/6/04 4:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=199.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Fusion Breakthrough?</span><hr size=1> RE:  possibility of going prompt-critical <br>
<br>
Commercial power reactors are designed to avoid prompt criticality.  They make use of &quot;delayed-neutrons&quot; to regulate the fission process and maintain criticality.<br>
<br>
=========  Side note  ==========<br>
<br>
Criticality means that enough neutrons survive from the fission process to 'maintain' the 'chain reaction', and this means that a constant power level is maintained.  Criticality is described by a simple relationship:<br>
<br>
k-effective (or k eff) = 1<br>
<br>
When a reactor is subcritical, i.e. k eff &lt; 1, the power is decreasing.  When the reactor is supercritical, k eff &gt; 1, and the reactor power increases.<br>
<br>
How much greater k eff is greater than or less than one determines how rapidly the power increases or decreases, respectively.<br>
<br>
Now back to &quot;delayed-neutrons&quot;.<br>
<br>
========================<br>
<br>
Each fission produces a pair of fission products and a few neutrons (2 or 3 or rarely 4) of assymetric mass.  For example, the nucleus of U-235 absorbs a neutron -&gt; an unstable U-236 nucleus, which may (most of the time) fission into<br>
<br>
Kr-87 and Ba-146 + 3 neutrons (plus gamma rays)<br>
<br>
but it could also fission to<br>
<br>
Br-87 and La-146 + 3 neutrons<br>
<br>
or <br>
<br>
Se-87 and Ce-146 + 3 neutrons.<br>
<br>
Se-87 decays (by beta emission) to Br-87, AND<br>
<br>
Br-87 is one of those nuclides that has the unique property of emitting a neutron - which is delayed for some seconds (about 56 seconds in the case of Br-87).  There are several other radionuclides such as I-137, Rb-93,94, Br-90,91 which also release delayed neutrons but in shorter time.<br>
<br>
The fission reactions mentioned above are just a few of over a hundred types of reactions possible.<br>
<br>
For U-235 fueled systems, about 0.65% of neutrons are delayed, and it is this delay which allows for control of the 'chain reaction'.<br>
<br>
In contrast, prompt neutrons have lifetimes on the order to 1E-4 seconds or less, and it is physically impossible to devise a control system that could work this fast.<br>
<br>
A good source for understanding reactor physics is:<br>
<br>
tis.eh.doe.gov/techstds/standard/hdbk1019/h1019v1.pdf<br>
