That's exactly what I was thinking. Also, 56 seconds is a very poor reaction time for an engine. As space travel develops, at some point the military will want a craft capable of fast orbit to surface dogfighting. If they use nuclear engines in these craft, they'll have to be capable of sudden changes in velocity. The only way those velocity changes are possible is if the reactor can provide more power in less time. <br>
<br>
Now there may not be a way of controlling a normal prompt-critical reaction, but if the reaction is dependent on a powered neutron source, adjustments can be made very quickly. 1 millisecond is a difficult amount of time to do anything mechanically. But a computer processor can operate orders of magnitudes faster, and can control the rate of power flow in real time. Since electrical waves propagate extremely fast (light speed being the limit), the control mechanism would simply need to add more or less power to the sonics. There'd still be some mechanical lag, but the lag would probably be about 200-500 ms. <br>
